<article id="post-554" class="post-554 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-general category-trains category-travel tag-around-the-world tag-beer tag-beijing tag-china">
	<header class="entry-header">
		
		<h2 class="entry-title"><a href="http://geoff.wp/2005/05/searching-for-the-tianjin-antique-market/" rel="bookmark">Searching for the Tianjin Antique Market</a></h2>	</header><!-- .entry-header -->

	
	
	<div class="entry-content">
		<p>Lonely Planet recommends going to Tianjin, especially to see the antique market there. It is said that a lot of the materials there were confiscated during the Cultural Revolution, and are now being sold to the dealers, who in turn sell it at the market. Theoretically, neat stuff, right?<br />
This brought Amy and I to hop on the first Beijing &#8211; Tianjen express train this morning. A jaunty 90-minute trip on a fairly zippy (and comfy) train that deposited us at a rather chaotic train station. We walked from there roughly south-west (&#8220;roughly&#8221; because the street grid is slightly skewed, and got us turned around more than once) when we stumbled across a rather large and bustling pedestrian mall.<br />
As Amy so aptly put it, this distracted us a while.<br />
 <a href="http://geoff.wp/2005/05/searching-for-the-tianjin-antique-market/#more-554" class="more-link">Continue reading<span class="screen-reader-text"> &#8220;Searching for the Tianjin Antique Market&#8221;</span></a></p>
	</div><!-- .entry-content -->

